    fix: 'Fixed 2026-07-07 — implemented both fixes together per this entry\'s own suggestion, since a validation gate is only as meaningful as the return measurement it\'s validating. (1) Validation gate: optimal_weight is still selected by maximizing calib_obs accuracy (unchanged), but set_ml_weight_global_cap() now only runs if that weight ALSO beats a neutral 0.5 baseline on expected value (avg_return_pct, not accuracy — consistent with the T232-OC4 EV convention used elsewhere) on val_obs, with a MIN_VAL_SAMPLES=15 floor matching the pattern already proven in T232-OC3/T234-SIG-INSAMPLE-GATE-TUNING. Removed the old `val_obs = observations[split:] or observations` fallback, which blurred the two slices back together (reintroducing in-sample bias) whenever validation was thin — now returns `applied: false` with an explicit reason instead. (2) Exit-price fix: exit_p previously used `_pclose[sig.stock_id][-1]` (whatever the MOST RECENT close happened to be), mixing holding periods from days to ~180 days (lookback_days) into one sweep. Now looks up each signal\'s own style-specific hold window via the existing `_OUTCOME_HOLD_DAYS` dict (the same convention outcomes_calibrate_apply/tune_style_profiles already use) and finds the first close at or after `signal_date + hold_days` — a signal whose hold window hasn\'t closed yet is correctly excluded as an unresolved observation, rather than measured against an arbitrary later date. Compile-checked (3.11 + 3.12, matches signal-engine\'s 3.11.15 container). Verified live on local dev: endpoint runs cleanly and correctly reports `applied: false` with "only 14 validation-slice observations (need 15)" given local dev\'s known-thin data (documented limitation, same ceiling hit by other fixes this session) — also unit-tested the accuracy/EV comparison helper in isolation with synthetic data to confirm the promotion-check arithmetic itself is correct.',
