    what: 'Rithmic is a low-latency futures execution and market-data platform (direct exchange connectivity to CME/CBOT etc.) used by professional and semi-professional futures traders — it is infrastructure, not an indicator or strategy. A futures contract is a leveraged (typically 10-20x via margin), expiring, nearly-24-hour-market agreement to buy/sell an asset at a fixed future price — categorically different from the equities (US/HK stocks) this app trades. Rithmic\'s value proposition (sub-millisecond order routing, real-time depth-of-book data, algo-trading APIs) exists specifically to serve latency-sensitive strategies like scalping and market-making.',
    fix: 'Not applicable — evaluated and rejected, three concrete reasons: (1) Asset-class mismatch: every service in this codebase (signal-engine, ranking-engine, decision-engine, paper-trading, the Fidelity/E*Trade broker-integration roadmap in project_broker_integration memory) is built around equities; Rithmic has no equities path, so adopting it would mean building a second, parallel trading system rather than extending this one. (2) Speed mismatch: this system\'s signals refresh on a schedule (5x/day per project_scheduler_schedule memory), not tick-by-tick — the entire architecture (REST calls across 11 microservices, DB-backed signal storage, scheduled batch tuning) is built for "recompute periodically and act deliberately," the opposite of what Rithmic exists to serve. (3) Cost/complexity for no payoff: Rithmic requires a funded futures account and a broker relationship that supports it — real setup and ongoing cost — for ultra-low-latency execution that nothing in the current signal/gate logic operates fast enough to use. If futures ever become a genuinely new asset class for this app (not just faster execution of the same equities strategies), that would need its own design doc — new data feeds, new margin/risk math, new contract-roll handling — rather than bolting onto the current equities pipeline. No further action taken.',
