    title: 'MD-VOLDRYUP1: post-open digest now also flags stocks trading meaningfully BELOW their normal volume (RVOL <= 0.5), reported in its own "Volume Dry-Up" section alongside the existing Volume Surge one',
    what: 'User: "we can keep the same [digest dedup-by-day behavior] now but also add a check for vol decrease suddenly can we?" — requested a mirror-image counterpart to the existing volume-surge detection (RVOL >= 1.5): stocks trading unusually quietly today vs. their 20-day average, which can signal evaporating conviction, often precedes a breakout once volume returns, or simply flags a stock coasting on no news.',
    fix: 'scheduler.py: the existing vol_surge loop in send_post_open_digest() now also buckets any stock with RVOL <= 0.5 into a new vol_dryup list (symmetric threshold to the existing 1.5x surge cutoff), sourced from the exact same stockai:live_prices / stockai:avg_volume Redis reads already used for vol_surge — no new data source. Sorted quietest-first (ascending RVOL, opposite of vol_surge\'s descending sort). Given its own independent same-day dedup tracking (vol_dryup_symbols in the Redis snapshot, mirroring vol_surge_symbols) so a stock already flagged as quiet in an earlier digest today does not repeat in a later one, consistent with the existing "only report what changed since the last check" design for every other section. Included in has_content so a dry-up-only digest still sends even with nothing else to report.\n\nemail_service.py: added a new vol_dryup parameter and its own "Volume Dry-Up (RVOL vs. 20d avg)" section (HTML table + plain-text block), rendered directly below the existing Volume Surge section — same row layout (symbol, RVOL, price, %change + accumulation/distribution/flat direction note), reusing the shared _vol_direction() helper (factored out to module scope so both sections use identical accumulation/distribution logic) rather than duplicating it. Subject line now also appends "N volume dry-up" when present, alongside the existing volume-surge count.\n\nAll 36 market-data tests pass (pre-existing, no test changes needed — purely additive scheduling/formatting mirroring already-tested vol_surge logic). Both files py_compile clean.',
    implementedNote: 'Done 2026-07-10, same session as MD-RVOL2 above. Follow-up same day (MD-VOLDIRECTION1): user asked whether low RVOL means selling — clarified it does not (RVOL measures intensity, not direction; low RVOL usually means neither buyers nor sellers are active) and that heavy SELLING is actually a HIGH-RVOL event with falling price, already partially covered by the existing accumulation/distribution direction tag. Per user\'s follow-up request to make that more prominent, split the single "Volume Surge" table into two clearly-labeled sub-sections — "Volume Surge — Selling" (red-tinted, surge + price down >= 0.5%) shown first since it is the more urgent case, then "Volume Surge — Buying" (surge + price up/flat) — instead of one mixed table with a small inline direction tag. Subject line now also separately counts "N selling on volume" / "N buying on volume".',
